Premise: The socio-economic factors, cultural influences, and healthcare access significantly impact the management of heart failure in African-American patients. These factors can make it difficult for the patient to engage in regular physical activities which are crucial for heart health.

Reasoning: In the context of this patient, his age and socio-economic condition may mean he has limited access to healthcare resources and may struggle to afford medications or regular check-ups. Living in an unsafe neighborhood can discourage outdoor activities, while his age and heart condition may also limit the intensity of exercises he can perform safely.

Solution: Encourage the patient to engage in light, indoor exercises, such as walking around the house, lifting light weights, or chair yoga. These exercises can help manage his heart condition while considering his age and neighborhood safety.

Anticipate Barrier: The patient may lack the knowledge or motivation to engage in these exercises, or he might face challenges in accessing resources such as weights or yoga equipment due to his financial condition.

Solve Barrier: Propose using household items as substitute weights, such as cans of food or water bottles. Also providing printed or digital guides can help him understand the exercises better.

Educate: Explain to the patient that regular physical activity can help manage his heart failure symptoms, improve his overall health, and enhance his quality of life. Stress the importance of starting slow and gradually increasing the intensity and duration of his workouts, always staying within his comfort and safety limits.